Those look like they were crowded out when the landowner planted another dense conifer as natural fencing (plus the red cedar should have been thinned at some point). column65: Two trees appear to have expanded into each other at ground level. This observation is about the trunk on the right in photos with both trunks. They are within a few feet of another, separate Western Redcedar, which is also reported in the Western Redcedar Dieback Map: https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/134931662. The tops of all three trees show in the overall canopy photo; this observation is about the one in the center of that photo. Tree does not show any tip dieback. It appears to have normal dieback of interior shaded branches, shown in one photo. There is also one small branch in the canopy with dead leaves shown in a canopy photo; it is probably from something breaking it, not dieback from stress.
